content:
Certainly! Creating a webpage to display the migration patterns of Monarch butterflies requires careful planning and design. Below is a basic structure and style for the webpage using HTML and CSS. Since we are not using JavaScript, we'll be using a static map image with markers overlaid using CSS for simplicity.

### HTML (index.html)

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Monarch Butterfly Migration</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Monarch Butterfly Migration in Sierra Madre Occidental</h1>
        <nav>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#map">Migration Map</a></li>
                <li><a href="#life-cycle">Life Cycle</a></li>
                <li><a href="#research">Scientific Research</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </header>

    <main>
        <section id="map">
            <h2>Migration Map</h2>
            <div class="map-container">
                <img src="sierra-madre-map.jpg" alt="Map of Sierra Madre Occidental" class="map">
                <div class="marker" style="top: 30%; left: 40%;">1</div>
                <div class="marker" style="top: 50%; left: 60%;">2</div>
                <div class="marker" style="top: 70%; left: 30%;">3</div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="life-cycle">
            <h2>Monarch Butterfly Life Cycle</h2>
            <p>The life cycle of a Monarch butterfly includes four stages: egg, larva (caterpillar), pupa (chrysalis), and adult butterfly. Each stage is crucial for the development and survival of the butterfly.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="research">
            <h2>Scientific Research</h2>
            <p>Recent studies have shown that Monarch butterflies use environmental cues to navigate during their migration. Conservation efforts are crucial to protect their habitats and ensure their survival.</p>
        </section>
    </main>

    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2023 Monarch Migration Project</p>
    </footer>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (styles.css)

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

header {
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: white;
    padding: 10px 0;
    text-align: center;
}

nav ul {
    list-style-type: none;
    padding: 0;
}

nav ul li {
    display: inline;
    margin: 0 15px;
}

nav ul li a {
    color: white;
    text-decoration: none;
}

main {
    padding: 20px;
}

.map-container {
    position: relative;
    max-width: 100%;
    overflow: hidden;
}

.map {
    width: 100%;
    display: block;
}

.marker {
    position: absolute;
    background-color: red;
    color: white;
    padding: 5px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    width: 20px;
    height: 20px;
    text-align: center;
    line-height: 20px;
}

footer {
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 10px 0;
    position: fixed;
    width: 100%;
    bottom: 0;
}
```

### Explanation

1. **HTML Structure**: The HTML file has a header with navigation links, a main section divided into three parts (map, life cycle, and research), and a footer.

2. **CSS Styling**: 
   - The `body` has a simple font and line-height for readability.
   - The `header` and `footer` have background colors for visual appeal.
   - The `nav` uses an inline list for navigation.
   - The `map-container` holds a static image of the Sierra Madre Occidental with markers positioned using absolute positioning.

3. **Markers**: Simple CSS markers are placed on the map using percentage-based positioning to simulate locations.

This is a basic setup that ensures accessibility and a visually appealing design. You can customize the styles further and replace the map image with a more detailed one that you have the rights to use.
